violation.” (DOJ argued that “state law requiring the signature of witnesses to an absentee ballot does not violate the [Voting Rights Act] ban on obstacles to voting.”) In truth, “our country hasn’t changed.” Rather, conservative Republicans gained control of the Supreme Court

, the Senate, the Executive, and statehouses across the country. That coalition is doing its best to drag America back to the days of Jim Crow laws by pretending that the racial animus that motivated those laws no longer exists. It does—and no amount of legal sophistry or feigned

impartiality can conceal that fact. Gun-toting white nationalists were welcomed into the Michigan statehouse; protestors in Minneapolis are tracked from rooftops by police with sniper scopes on assault rifles. There are many reasons that police officers and voter registrars

discriminate against black citizens. One reason is that they believe they can get away with it. Trump, Sessions, and Barr have signaled that discriminatory conduct by state officials will be defended or ignored so long as those actions preserve white supremacy in shrinking

bastions scattered across the country. The U.S. Attorney and County Attorney for Minneapolis stumbled badly on Thursday afternoon when they held a news conference in which they announced they needed to “get their ducks in a row” and that “there is other evidence that does not

support a criminal charge.” See CBS, “‘We Have To Do This Right’: Hennepin County Attorney Mike Freeman Says George Floyd Investigation Will Take Time.” Those prosecutors would not be so cautious in filing charges if a black man killed a white officer in the same manner.
